From: Johanan Lai <lai.johanan@gmail.com>
Date: Fri, 5 Aug 2016 15:18:53 -0700
Subject: [PATCH] ADMINUI-2310 Tooltip to clarify vCPU and CPU Cap definition
 in package creation form

---
 www/js/tpl/packages-form.hbs | 4 ++--
 1 file changed, 2 insertions(+), 2 deletions(-)

diff --git a/www/js/tpl/packages-form.hbs b/www/js/tpl/packages-form.hbs
index 7c0fb885..1beb9832 100644
--- a/www/js/tpl/packages-form.hbs
+++ b/www/js/tpl/packages-form.hbs
@@ -155,7 +155,7 @@
               name="vcpus" placeholder="cpus">
           <p class="help-block">Applies to KVMs only.
             <a data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="bottom" data-trigger="hover"
-              title='"Virtual" CPUs that the guest OS sees as physical CPUs.'>
+              title="Number of virtual CPUs presented to the guest OS. Required when creating a KVM.">
               What is this?</a>
           </p>
         </div>
@@ -175,7 +175,7 @@
           </div>
           <p class="help-block">Minimum: 20%
             <a data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="bottom" data-trigger="hover"
-              title="Upper bound for the computational time tasks are allocated. For example, a CPU cap of 75% means that all threads in a zone get to use 75% of a single CPU core, disregarding system tasks and CPU shares. To account for system tasks also requiring computational time, this should be set higher than necessary, e.g. over 400% if you require 4 CPUs' worth of computational time.">
+              title="Upper bound for the computational time the instance can use. Applies to all instance types. For example, 200% would give the instance up to 2 vCPUs worth of computational time. To account for CPU time taken by system tasks, set this higher than the number of vCPUs the instance requires.">
               What is this?</a>
           </p>
         </div>
